EDUPAGE. Edupage, a twice-weekly summary of news items on information
technology, is provided as a service by EDUCOM -- a consortium of leading
colleges and universities seeking to transform education through the use of
information technology.

COMPUTERS & THE ENVIRONMENT. An Arthur D. Little study says that
telecommuting, teleconferencing and teleshopping can cut pollution, reduce
traffic congestion, and provide other environmental benefits.  For example,
a 10-20% reduction in trips would save 3.5 billion gallons of gas yearly.
(Atlanta Constitution 12/2/93 A19)

SURGE OF THE KNOWLEDGE WORKERS. In spite of expectations to the contrary,
more than three-fifths of new jobs created in the U.S. last year went not
to fast-food and blue collar workers but to managers and professionals.
(New York Times 12/2/93 C1)

EXPLODING LAPTOPS. NEC has recalled a large number of its laptop computers
following reports that the units explode when booted up.
(Telecommunications Policy Review 11/28/93 p.10)

CHIP SUPPLY STABLE. The Sumitomo Chemical plant in Japan, which was damaged
in an accident last July, is back in production, thus averting a feared
shortage of microprocessing chips. The plant manufactures 50% of the epoxy
resins used to encase the chips. (Wall Street Journal 12/1/93 A8)

AT&T DOWNSIZE LIKELY. AT&T is drawing up plans that could eliminate several
thousand jobs. (New York Times 12/2/93 C3)

PC MAIL ORDERS COOL OFF. The mail-order PC business, which claimed 12% of
the consumer computer market this year, is leveling off, and industry
observers expect the phenomenon to decline over the next decade. "It's very
clear that the glory days of the mail-order business are over," noted a
computer retail consultant. (Wall Street Journal 12/1/93 B1)

APPLE SHUNNED FOR BENEFITS POLICY.  Apple's plans to build an $80 million
office complex near Austin, TX, are in jeopardy. County officials have
refused to give the company a property tax abatement because of Apple's
policy of giving health benefits to unwed and same-sex partners. (New York
Times 12/2/93 A1)

SUPERCOMPUTER MARKET SHAKY. The entrepreneurial supercomputer market is
ready to "implode," according to an industry market researcher.
Contributing factors include the ending of the Cold War and the current
administration's focus on computer communications for the masses rather
than high-performance computing for the elite. In addition, IBM and Cray
have decided to compete aggressively in the $2-billion market, putting
smaller companies at a disadvantage. (Wall Street Journal 12/1/93 B4)

PLANNED OBSOLESCENCE. The FCC has proposed new rules requiring that cable
boxes be replaced by small paperback-book- sized cartridges that snap into
newly designed television sets and VCRs. "The sets will probably be on the
market some time in 1996," says an FCC economist. (Miami Herald 12/1/93 C3)

BATTLE OF THE BOXES. The battle over who will produce the next- generation
TV set-top decoder boxes is heating up. Competing systems offered by
Hewlett-Packard, Scientific-Atlanta and General Instrument are aimed at
accommodating digital signals and interactive services, but each has
different technical standards. (Wall Street Journal 12/2/93 B12)

PUSHING THE DEREGULATORY ENVELOPE. Bell Canada has been aggressively
pushing the limits of Canadian telecom regulations by going ahead with
trials of future information highway services currently prohibited under
existing regulations. The federal regulatory agency has turned a blind eye
because they are still tests and Bell is not charging, yet, for the
services. (Ottawa Citizen 12/02/93 D13).

CABLE FIRMS UNITE. Five of the nation's largest cable companies are
investors in Teleport Communications Group, a joint venture that would
position the cable firms to compete head-to-head with regional phone
companies in the competitive access business, as well as a host of new
services such as video telephony and PCS. The five companies are: Time
Warner, TCI, Cox Enterprises, Comcast Corp. and Continental Cablevision.
(New York Times 12/2/93 C1; Wall Street Journal 12/2/93 B8)
 
FRAME RELAY TRIAL SUCCESSFUL. A technical trial of frame relay switching
systems was declared a success, paving the way for offering end-to-end
national frame relay service for highly efficient data transmission along
predetermined routes. T-1 circuits connected three sites at Bell Atlantic,
Bellcore, and WilTel, and TCP/IP and Novell Netware protocols were used and
evaluated. (Corporate communications)   

BELL ATLANTIC'S BIG PLANS. Bell Atlantic predicts it will deliver
multimedia services to more than 1 million homes by 1995 and more than 8
million by 2000. (Wall Street Journal 12/2/93 B12)

DIGITAL PHONE SERVICE. New Brunswick Telephone became Canada's first phone
company able to provide computerized digital service to every subscriber -
the first step in transforming the company's network into a high-speed,
electronic information highway. (Toronto Globe & Mail 11/30/93 B7).

WHITTLE REPORT. Whittle Communications, producers of Channel One, has
raised its advertising rates 26% from a year ago, and some major
advertisers have decided to drop out. But despite losing some of its big
guns, Whittle projects a 16% revenue gain this year and expects to be 91%
to 93% sold out for the 1993-94 school year. (Wall Street Journal 12/1/93
B5)

VOICE MEETING PLANNER. Voice Organizer, a $200 device the size of a small
tape recorder, allows a person to record voice reminders of meeting places
and times. It's available from Voice Power Technology of Canoga Park,
California. (Atlanta Constitution 12/2/93 G2)

IN-FLIGHT PHONES AND MORE. Starting in January, In-Flight Phones will
install digital passenger communications and entertainment systems on all
of America West's 85 aircraft. Passengers will be able to make phone calls,
send faxes, transmit computer data, play video games and shop using video
screens installed in seatbacks. (Wall Street Journal 11/30/93 B4)

COUCH POTATOES SHOULD LOOK ELSEWHERE. QVC will launch a second home
shopping service "targeting busy, active people." It will offer products in
sports, health and beauty, family life, the home, entertainment, style and
travel." (Atlanta Constitution 12/2/93 G1)  

ELECTRONIC CENSORSHIP. As the battle over a publication ban in a criminal
trial continues to rage, the University of Toronto became the latest to
stop carrying an Internet bulletin board that specifically discloses banned
information and discussion about the case, but it has become virtually
impossible to intercept the electronic exchange of such information.
(Toronto Globe & Mail 12/02/93 A4).

BACK TO ADAM & EVE. Family Tree Maker for Windows, which is designed to
record family information and print out family trees, can record
information for about one million relatives. It's from Banner Blue Software
in Freemont, California. (Atlanta Constitution 12/2/93)

CAUSE93 PAPERS ONLINE.  The full texts of many papers to be presented next
week at the CAUSE93 conference in San Diego are now accessible online. Send
e-mail to search@cause.colorado.edu containing the one-line message:
libsearch cnc93.

